1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,240
Hello, and welcome. Today we're opening Chapter 12 of the Handbook of Face Recognition.

2
00:00:08,840 --> 00:00:19,820
To make sense of a face, a computer first has to find the parts, the eyes, the nose, the mouth,

3
00:00:21,300 --> 00:00:28,700
88 tiny points, and the need to land in under a tenth of a second. The chapter is built around

4
00:00:29,260 --> 00:00:37,420
six questions. Where are the eyes? What's the framework? How do we fit the landmarks?

5
00:00:38,760 --> 00:00:47,720
Does any of it actually work? And what comes next? Let's start at the very beginning. Where do

6
00:00:47,720 --> 00:00:56,880
landmarks actually help? First, face recognition. You compare two faces by lining up the points.

7
00:00:58,760 --> 00:01:07,020
3D reconstruction. These flat dots become the seeds for a full 3D model of the head.

8
00:01:08,820 --> 00:01:15,080
Cartoon or sketch. Trace the points and you get a stylized drawing.

9
00:01:16,580 --> 00:01:22,860
Pose estimation. Figure out which way the head is turning from the landmarks alone.

10
00:01:24,580 --> 00:01:31,860
3D expression analysis. Read a smile or a frown from where the points move.

11
00:01:34,240 --> 00:01:41,840
And beautification. Every modern photo filter starts right here. Start with the obvious fix.

12
00:01:42,700 --> 00:01:47,440
To find an eye, search the box where an eye should be and take the darkest spot.

13
00:01:49,420 --> 00:01:57,940
On a clean, front-facing photo it works. Then the real world shows up.

14
00:01:59,960 --> 00:02:04,820
A shadow falls across the face and the edge it locked onto is gone.

15
00:02:07,480 --> 00:02:11,480
The head turns and the eye slides straight out of the box.

16
00:02:13,700 --> 00:02:19,700
The face moves closer. Then pulls away and the box stops fitting at all.

17
00:02:23,780 --> 00:02:31,720
Illumination. Pose. Scale. One rigid box. Three ways to break.

18
00:02:34,220 --> 00:02:39,780
The answer isn't a better box. It's knowing what a face is. It's shape

19
00:02:40,500 --> 00:02:42,720
and the few ways it's allowed to move.

20
00:02:44,740 --> 00:02:50,620
That's the framework we built next. Every method in this chapter shares the same skeleton.

21
00:02:52,220 --> 00:03:03,260
First detect the face. Then crop. Then find the points. And finally refine.

22
00:03:04,840 --> 00:03:10,300
Only the finder step changes. Everything else stays the same.

23
00:03:11,120 --> 00:03:19,380
The shape model is built on a simple idea. Every face is the mean face plus a few learned tweaks.

24
00:03:20,940 --> 00:03:28,100
Each tweak is a mode of variation. The first mode usually controls scale.

25
00:03:29,060 --> 00:03:39,020
The second rotation. The third expression. Keep about fifteen of these modes and you can

26
00:03:39,020 --> 00:03:47,040
rebuild almost any face. Find the eyes first. They're the easiest part to spot round, dark,

27
00:03:47,800 --> 00:03:53,320
framed by lighter skin. Once you have them, you have a coordinate system.

28
00:03:54,620 --> 00:04:01,120
Scale. Rotation. The rough position of every other point all from the eyes.

29
00:04:02,140 --> 00:04:10,300
Here's the whole idea in one line. Any face is the mean face plus a few learned adjustments.

30
00:04:12,080 --> 00:04:16,100
Start with the mean, the average shape. The same for everyone.

31
00:04:17,540 --> 00:04:24,060
Now turn the first dial. Mode one is with the face grows wider than narrower.

32
00:04:27,440 --> 00:04:30,960
The second dial is height taller than shorter.

33
00:04:34,140 --> 00:04:40,540
A third opens a smile. A fourth lifts the brows.

34
00:04:42,840 --> 00:04:48,520
That's the whole model. A mean shape and a handful of numbers one per mode.

35
00:04:49,700 --> 00:04:55,260
Dial them in and you rebuild any face. You can watch the points settle.

36
00:04:56,700 --> 00:05:02,180
Starting from the mean shape, every round nudges them closer to where they belong.

37
00:05:03,280 --> 00:05:06,400
Does any of this actually work? Time to measure.

38
00:05:07,440 --> 00:05:12,680
We put RFV ASM head-to-head with a plain active shape model.

39
00:05:14,740 --> 00:05:19,480
Three standard benchmarks. BioID, ferret, and AR.

40
00:05:22,660 --> 00:05:29,660
First, accuracy. On every data set, the refined method lands closer to the truth the bars climb

41
00:05:29,660 --> 00:05:43,980
higher. And it isn't slower for it. Side by side, RFV ASM fits a face in less time on a single CPU thread.

42
00:05:46,520 --> 00:05:52,700
Now zoom into the points. The error drops across almost all 88 of them, not just on average.

43
00:05:55,360 --> 00:06:02,680
And the cumulative curve rises sooner. More face is solved inside a tight error budget.

44
00:06:04,800 --> 00:06:10,840
More accurate. And faster. That's the result. So that is the chapter.

45
00:06:12,300 --> 00:06:18,560
A shape model. A neighborhood pattern. An iterative search.

46
00:06:19,840 --> 00:06:25,400
Together, the engine of face geometry for over a decade. What did we deliver?

47
00:06:26,560 --> 00:06:31,000
Real-time, landmark fitting on standard frontal faces.

48
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:38,480
What's still unsolved? Big head turns. Heavy occlusion.

49
00:06:40,320 --> 00:06:46,680
And what's next? The deep learning wave the authors could already see coming.

50
00:06:47,400 --> 00:06:55,440
Chapter 12 was written in 2011. Here is what happened in the 15 years after. 2011.

51
00:06:57,240 --> 00:07:05,300
Shape models still held a throne. Beautiful, interpretable, but slow on anything that wasn't

52
00:07:05,300 --> 00:07:12,720
looking straight at the camera. 2012, 2013. Cascade regression took over.

53
00:07:13,680 --> 00:07:18,320
Instead of fitting a shape, the model just learned to jump.

54
00:07:19,680 --> 00:07:25,560
Each step, every point, moved closer to its target. 2017.

55
00:07:27,180 --> 00:07:31,000
FAN. Heatmap Convolutional Networks.

56
00:07:32,560 --> 00:07:37,240
Instead of pointing at one pixel, every pixel gets to vote.

57
00:07:38,200 --> 00:07:46,440
The brightest spot wins. Profile faces an occlusion that broke the old methods finally solved.

58
00:07:47,440 --> 00:08:01,100
2020. MediaPipe. 468 dense points. A full-face mesh. Running on your phone at 30 frames per second.

59
00:08:02,060 --> 00:08:10,360
The technology behind every modern face filter. 2022 and beyond. Full 3D mesh.

60
00:08:11,600 --> 00:08:18,720
Recovered from a single photo. Identity. Expression. Head pose.

61
00:08:20,500 --> 00:08:25,500
All separated. All controllable. In one model. Three poles.

62
00:08:29,300 --> 00:08:37,600
Accuracy. Interpretability. Real time. No method holds all three at one. Choosing two out of the

63
00:08:37,600 --> 00:08:47,900
three that is still the central design question. Six papers. 15 years. One rabbit hole.

64
00:08:49,140 --> 00:08:55,660
Chapter 12. Sits right in the middle of this trajectory. The bridge between the

65
00:08:55,660 --> 00:09:02,400
classical era and everything that came after. Where landmark localization started.

66
00:09:04,240 --> 00:09:05,200
And where it's going.
